The metal-ocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-purpose cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Domestic and persistent virus
HIV protease is an HIV protein that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus division caused by the HIV protease, no mature infectious virus particles would occur.
When we switch off the HIV protease, we also eliminate the proliferation of the virus in the patient's body, the scientists in the press report, published by the Institute for Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the work published in the Scientific Journal of Medical Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically changed further.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The impact of this series of substances against the HIV protease levels tested in the test tube, also against their persistent (resistant) variants obtained from HIV infected patients.
