The Coat of the Dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: The two-metre-long and 1.50-meter-sized animal ran on two strong hind legs, had a long skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle collars and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would be nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the journal Science of Thursday.
The animal lived some 215 million years ago in today’s New Mexico, which was on the equator in a dry zone of the supercontinent of Pangea.
Tawa opens a new window on the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us much about the relationship, spread and characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other palaeontologists began digging on the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones one day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the trias, reports team member Randall Irmis from the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as new species.
During the excavation they combined the remains of a total of five individuals.
Fund confirms theories on Dino Early History
The name "Tawa" is derived from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an extraordinary find: "Dinosaur fossils from the trias are extremely rare, usually you only find individual fragments."
Other dinosaur experts don't necessarily share the enthusiasm.
Especially spectacular is this find not, but he confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
After the current teaching, the dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these original dinos is usually controversial.
For example, the experts discuss when the lizards split into their three main lines of development: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, which are known as "long-tails", the four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and the plants milling ornithicia (bird-basinsaurier), which included, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
After the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropode.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
At the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of air bags, as they also have the descendants of the Theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the respiration of the birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
At Tawa hallae also the bones of the spine were apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropode with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the huge sauropods later also had airbags and lightweight bones, probably the common ancestor of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migration waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers say that the lizards appeared there for the first time.
Thus, the three lines of development began to differ early and spread from South America to all parts of the earth, which at that time still formed a single land mass as a supercontinent Pangea.
The fact that the team, together with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related, Theropods, speaks for this.
The three cannot come from a common immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe that there were at least three migration waves to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
There are, of course, contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says Bonner Palaeontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could result in a distorted picture, because in South America just a lot of primitive Dino fossils have been preserved, while on other continents nothing can be found.
As the dinosaurs managed to develop from a relatively rare side line of the reptile strain to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of the Middle Ages, it is still puzzling.
During the trias, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example, with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and the flying auraurs and with many more axes.
Towards the end of the trias, the dinosaurs spread around the world and developed many new species, while the relationship at the border from the trias to the Jura died out.
Success Story Not Lasting Forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass death that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so that they could beat the competition out of the field.
The success story certainly did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact of a group of animals turned into flowers, which had already developed in the Trias and since then had a shadowing age: mammals.
