Support for brake manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As with the ABS anti-lock braking system at the time, and as is the case with the ESP stability control, emergency braking systems need to become a necessary equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already required for all newly authorised passenger cars and light small carriers, for the remaining vehicles a standstill period was set until the end of February 2011.
The measures adopted by the European Union are aimed at improving the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many road accidents due to their working methods.
The task of the emergency brake assist is to apply more pressure to the brakes in the event of a critical brake manoeuvre, which detects the system on the brake pedal based on the braking strength performed by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident were no longer able to hit the brake pedal before the collision, and half of them had not braked with full force.
Up to 1.100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the braking system and thereby reduces the braking time and thus also the brake distance a car travels during braking.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assist, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented every year.
There would be even fewer accidents - one expects that every fourth accident could be prevented by personal injury - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects (via radar or camera) obstacles and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system will help him increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already inevitable, the brake assist exerts maximum pressure on the brakes in order to minimise the damage.
