CNMV has also announced that this offer is aimed at acquiring 550,0008 shares from Federico Paternina at a price of EUR 7.65 per share, which in turn is 8.95 % of the capital of the company, which consists of EUR 6,142,786 in shares admitted to Madrid and Bilbao.
Furthermore, it has been announced that 5,592,778 million shares have been fixed, which cannot be transferred in any way until the tender has been concluded and whose price has been determined by Federico Paternina in accordance with law.
New programmes for the assessment of vehicles
In these days of storms and accidents not only the car workshops deserve
Every day thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are dragged into workshops where an assessor has to assess the damage caused and the cost of repair.
No one accident is the same and the calculation of the costs for the parts and hours of work can be a lengthy and complicated task.
The calculation of the repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros by hand, including parts and hours of work, may take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest information technology tools, it is a matter of minutes
Therefore, almost 100 % of the assessors use this type of system.
The service and application providers for the assessment of accidents and repairs collect the information they receive from manufacturers to process them afterwards and to offer them to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American group Solera, is the market leader; 80% of all reports are produced with their products.
The other two companies competing in the tool market for the assessment and preparation of a report are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data the manufacturers provide is anything but simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, Sales Manager of Audatex, 63 manufacturers and importers are working together, each of them providing the information in a different format.
Moreover, the volume of data to be processed is becoming ever bigger, up to the point that more versions, variants and motorizations have been on the market in the last five years than in the entire fifteen years before.
As soon as a new car enters the market, the company will start work.
It is a laborious task, for every single one of the aber thousand vehicle parts must be catagolysed and its price entered.
In addition, each model creates an "intelligent" graphic image on which to "click" different parts of the vehicle.
In the case of a much sold model, work can be completed in a week if the procedure is carried out quickly.
If it is a less common car, it can take up to three or four months. Currently, Audatex has 99.2% of the car sold in Spain with complete information.
Among the more exclusive models, they have information about the Porsche models, but not about Ferrari or Lamborghini.
With regard to the roadside vehicle fleet, it is over 99%.
For the execution of documentation work and the production of databases, Audatex has eight centres distributed worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, the USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) and each of them has specialised in certain brands.
The National Headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
More than a hundred technicians (normally mechanics) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million euros annually in the preparation of these databases.
Each month they record 2.5 million data and their customers receive updates every second day.
The development of this huge flow of information enables companies to use it in different ways and thus offer different products.
The most common use is the use for repairs and repairs, but depending on the country there are also tools for managing scrap parts or for calculating the fault or residual value of a car.
